I'm a software engineer, researcher, and product builder based in Vienna.

I've spent the last two and a half decades writing software across industries — telecommunications during the GSM boom in Austria, surgical navigation systems in medical tech, eight years at [NIM](https://nim.org) (Nuremberg Institute for Market Decisions), Chief Founding Engineer at [ZML](https://zml.ai) building a Zig-based AI inference framework focused on performance, and now running my own company: [AI Research & Technology Lab GmbH](https://technologylab.ai).

## What I'm Building

**[QualCode](https://qualcode.ai)** — AI-powered qualitative coding for researchers. It runs two LLMs as independent raters (OpenAI + Anthropic), automatically computes inter-rater reliability (Cohen's kappa, Krippendorff's alpha), and produces audit-ready output. Built for the dual-coding standard that serious qualitative research requires. GDPR-compliant, EU infrastructure.

**[LaBrowser](https://labrowser.technologylab.ai)** — A research browser for behavioral studies. Captures structured interaction data — navigation, queries, AI prompts and responses, clicks — from study participants, with a researcher console for study design and analysis. Addresses a gap that screen recording and think-alouds can't fill.

## Background

I've been building things at the edges of disciplines for a long time.

At NIM I spent eight years as a senior researcher and technology lab manager — doing research myself, and building the infrastructure that made otherwise impossible research possible. That included a fully automated GPT-4 market research agent ([SurveySeed](/projects/surveyseed/)), an Arduino-based sensor synchronization device for multi-seat biosignals labs, reaction time measurement tools for behavioral economics, online shop environments for controlled studies (web and native mobile), and a research browser prototype that later inspired LaBrowser — among other things. I also did a significant amount of AI research: image models, voice models, multimodal models, training, fine-tuning — a broad range of applied work.

In open source: I created [⚡ZAP⚡](https://zigzap.org), the first production-ready HTTP web framework for [Zig](https://ziglang.org), which I presented at SYCL 2023. [Telekasten.nvim](https://github.com/nvim-telekasten/telekasten.nvim) started as my own note-taking setup in Neovim and ended up with a few thousand users. Before that, [Sublime_ZK](https://github.com/renerocksai/sublime_zk) did the same for SublimeText — and when people asked for a version that didn't require SublimeText, I built [Sublimeless_ZK](/projects/sublimeless_zk/), a standalone Zettelkasten app.

I've also [built a CPU from scratch](/projects/rrisc/), trained convolutional neural networks for logo detection [in 2017](/projects/brille/), and written not one but two presentation systems — first a [Godot game engine-based slideshow](/projects/bullets/), then [Slides](/projects/slides/) in Zig (presented at SYCL), which has since been ported to Raylib as [RaySlides](https://github.com/technologylab-ai/rayslides).

The common thread isn't the domain. It's seeing a gap — usually from being close enough to a real problem to feel it — and then building from first principles rather than just reaching for the obvious tool. I didn't build a Kanban board. I built [OMS](/blog/2025-12-09--oms-1/). I didn't build another slide deck app. I built a [presentation system on a game engine](/projects/bullets/), then [rewrote it in Zig](/projects/slides/), then ported it to Raylib. That's just how it goes.

## How I Work

Almost entirely in the terminal. Neovim, tmux, command line. Zig and Python are my primary languages, though I've written production code in C, C++ and enough others to get into trouble.

Since late 2025 I've been a serious vibe coder — Claude Code fundamentally changed how I work, and the shift is real enough that I've been thinking and writing about it. Running a [one-man company](/blog/2025-12-09--oms-1/) forces you to think carefully about leverage: what compounds, what doesn't, and how to build systems that work for you rather than the other way around. That thinking shows up in the blog too.

